const e="profit-loss-diagram",o="Your First Profit/Loss Diagram",t="7 min",i=[{screen_type:"hook",visual:"ðŸ“ŠðŸ“ˆ",headline:"One chart shows your entire trade risk",text:"Professional traders look at P/L diagrams before EVERY trade. It shows max profit, max loss, and breakeven - instantly. If you can read this chart, you can trade options safely."},{screen_type:"definition",headline:"What is a Profit/Loss (P/L) Diagram?",text:"A P/L diagram is a visual chart showing your profit or loss at every possible stock price at expiration. The X-axis = stock price. The Y-axis = your profit/loss. One glance tells you everything you need to know.",visual:"ðŸ“‰",highlight_words:["X-axis = stock price","Y-axis = profit/loss","at expiration"]},{screen_type:"analogy",headline:"Think of it like a mountain range",text:"Imagine you're hiking. The elevation chart shows where you'll be above sea level (profit) or below (loss) at each mile marker...",interactive:"tap_to_reveal",reveal_sections:[{label:"Valley (below sea level)",content:"This is your MAX LOSS zone. The lowest point shows the worst-case scenario. For option buyers, this is the premium you paid."},{label:"Sea level (break even)",content:"This is where you cross from loss to profit. Your breakeven point. Above = making money. Below = losing money."},{label:"Mountain peak (above sea level)",content:"This is your PROFIT zone. The higher you go, the more you make. For calls, it goes up infinitely. For puts, it has a ceiling."}]},{screen_type:"key_terms",headline:"Reading a P/L Diagram",cards:[{term:"Breakeven Point",definition:"Stock price where you neither profit nor lose",example:"Bought $100 call for $5 premium = breakeven at $105. Below $105 = loss. Above = profit."},{term:"Max Loss",definition:"The most you can lose on the trade",example:"For option buyers: always just the premium. Bought for $500 = max loss is $500. That's it. Ever."},{term:"Max Profit",definition:"The most you can make (if there is a cap)",example:"Calls = unlimited (stock can go to infinity). Puts = limited (stock can only go to $0). Spreads have defined max profit."}]},{screen_type:"interactive_example",headline:"Long Call P/L Diagram Builder",description:"Move the sliders to see how your P/L diagram changes",inputs:[{name:"Stock Price Now",type:"slider",min:50,max:200,default:100},{name:"Strike Price",type:"slider",min:80,max:150,default:110},{name:"Premium Paid",type:"slider",min:1,max:20,default:5}],teaching_points:["Notice: Max loss is always the premium (flat line at bottom)","Breakeven = Strike + Premium ($110 + $5 = $115)","Profit is UNLIMITED as stock goes higher (line goes up forever)"]},{screen_type:"multiple_choice",question:"You bought a call for $8 premium with a $150 strike. At what stock price do you break even?",options:["$150","$142","$158","$166"],correct:2,xp_reward:10,explanation_correct:"Perfect! Breakeven = Strike + Premium = $150 + $8 = $158. Below $158 = you're losing money. At exactly $158 = you break even. Above $158 = pure profit. This is your critical number.",explanation_wrong:"Remember the formula: Breakeven (call) = Strike + Premium. You paid $8 to have the right to buy at $150, so you need the stock at $158 just to recover your costs. Above that = profit."},{screen_type:"multiple_choice",question:"On a long call P/L diagram, what's your max loss?",options:["Unlimited","The strike price","The premium you paid","It depends on the stock price"],correct:2,xp_reward:10,explanation_correct:"Exactly! This is CRITICAL: when you BUY options (calls or puts), your max loss is ALWAYS just the premium. Stock goes to zero? You lose the premium. Stock goes up 500%? You still can only lose the premium if you're wrong. Defined risk!",explanation_wrong:"This is the beauty of buying options: your loss is CAPPED at the premium you paid. No matter how bad things get (stock to zero, bankruptcy, whatever), you can only lose what you spent upfront. That's the power of defined risk."},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"TSLA at $250. You bought a $270 call for $10. TSLA hits $300. What's your profit?",options:["$2,000","$3,000","$5,000","$1,000"],correct:0,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Nailed it! Stock at $300, you can buy at $270 = $30 intrinsic value Ã— 100 shares = $3,000. Minus your $1,000 premium = $2,000 profit. That's a 200% return while the stock moved 20%!",explanation_wrong:"Let's calculate: Stock at $300, your strike is $270 = $30/share of value. That's $3,000 per contract. You paid $1,000 (10 Ã— 100), so profit = $3,000 - $1,000 = $2,000. Watch the Ã— 100 multiplier!"},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"Looking at a P/L diagram, you see the profit line goes up infinitely to the right. What type of option is this?",options:["A call option (profit unlimited as stock rises)","A put option (profit capped at $0)","Both calls and puts look like this","This is impossible"],correct:0,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Exactly! A call's P/L line goes up infinitely because stocks can theoretically go to infinity. A put's line would go down (profit as stock drops) but STOPS at $0 since stocks can't go negative. Shape tells you the strategy!",explanation_wrong:"Look at the direction: line going UP to the right = profit from stock going UP = CALL option. If it was a put, the line would slope DOWN to the left (profit as stock drops) and stop at $0 because that's the floor for stock prices."},{screen_type:"summary_cards",headline:"P/L Diagram Mastery",cards:[{front:"What does a P/L diagram show?",back:"Your profit/loss at EVERY possible stock price at expiration. X-axis = stock price, Y-axis = your P/L. One glance = full risk picture."},{front:"Key numbers to find on every diagram",back:"1) Max Loss (bottom of diagram) 2) Breakeven (where line crosses $0) 3) Max Profit (top or unlimited). These 3 numbers define your trade."},{front:"How to spot a long call vs long put?",back:"Call = line goes UP to the right (unlimited). Put = line goes DOWN to the left (capped at $0). Max loss for both = flat line at -Premium."}]},{screen_type:"celebration",xp_earned:70,total_xp:360,badge:"ðŸ“Š Chart Reader",badge_description:"You can read P/L diagrams like a pro!",celebration_message:"Incredible progress! You've completed Unit 1. You now understand what options are and how they work. Ready for Unit 2: trading them!",streak_bonus:!1,next_lesson_preview:{title:"Buying Your First Call",description:"Learn when, why, and how to execute your first bullish trade",unlock_status:"unlocked"}}],a={lesson_id:e,title:o,estimated_time:t,screens:i};export{a as default,t as estimated_time,e as lesson_id,i as screens,o as title};
